dict.string: Save All App Icons to Icon Folder

#!/bin/bash
# Retrieve Keyboard Maestro variables Local__AppPaths="$KMVAR_Local__AppPaths" Local__IconFolder="$KMVAR_Local__IconFolder"
# Ensure IFS is set to newline only to handle spaces in filenames IFS=$'\n'
# Loop over each app path for appPath in $Local__AppPaths; do # Path to the application's Info.plist INFO_PLIST="${appPath}/Contents/Info.plist"
# Extract the name of the primary icon from the Info.plist (if available) ICON_NAME=$(defaults read "${INFO_PLIST}" CFBundleIconFile 2>/dev/null)
# If CFBundleIconFile doesn't have an extension, add .icns if [[ "$ICON_NAME" && ! "$ICON_NAME" == *.* ]]; then ICON_NAME="${ICON_NAME}.icns" fi
# Build the initial path to the icon assuming it's in the Resources directory ICON_PATH="${appPath}/Contents/Resources/${ICON_NAME}"
# If the icon is not directly in the Resources directory, search for it in subdirectories if [[ ! -f "$ICON_PATH" ]]; then ICON_PATH=$(find "${appPath}/Contents/Resources" -name "${ICON_NAME}" -print | head -n 1) fi
# Check if an icon file was found if [[ -f "$ICON_PATH" ]]; then # Extract the app name to use as the png file name appName=$(basename "${appPath}" .app)
# Full path for the output icon file iconOutputPath="${Local__IconFolder}/${appName}.png"
# Check if a file with the same name already exists if [[ ! -f "$iconOutputPath" ]]; then # Use 'sips' to convert the .icns to .png and resize it sips -s format png "${ICON_PATH}" --out "${iconOutputPath}" --resampleWidth 64 fi fi done
# Reset IFS back to default unset IFS
